SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 835
By Walley
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Jonathan Kerry
Blackwood.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Jonathan Kerry Blackwood; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Blackwood was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, Jonathan Blackwood was born on June 30, 1947, in Memphis to Jimmie
and Alese Blalock Blackwood; he attended public schools in Fayette County and received a
degree in history from Tennessee Technological University; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Blackwood earned his Juris Doctor degree from the University of
Memphis, and he began his legal career as an assistant district attorney, in which position he
served for ten years; and
WHEREAS, Jonathan Blackwood served as the circuit judge for the 25th Judicial District
for twenty years before serving as senior judge, covering all ninety-five counties, for the final ten
years of his career; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Blackwood was deeply devoted to his family, and he remained true to
family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his wife of fifty years,
Julia Jarrell Blackwood; brother, William Steven (Helen) Blackwood; sisters, Brenda (Wayne)
Keller and Beverly (Wayne) Smith; and several nieces, nephews, great-nieces, and great-
nephews; and
SJR0835
013602
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Jonathan Blackwood was preceded in death by his parents and a nephew,
Benjamin Smith; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Blackwood leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Jonathan Kerry
Blackwood, reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to
living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Blackwood.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
